r Pearl Harbor he was commissioned at the Anti-Aircraft School, served as a battery commander and intelligence officer, and finally moved into classified work and the Air Corps."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Pearl Harbor remade him at sixty-one","body":"The Grace executive had enlisted in New York’s Seventh Regiment before the war; after Pearl Harbor — at sixty-one — he was commissioned at the Anti-Aircraft School, commanded a battery, served as an intelligence officer, and finished in classified work for the Air Corps."}],"cross_connections":[],"career":[{"role":"Employee","organization":"W.R. Grace and Company","start_year":1934,"notes":"Employed by W.R. Grace from 1934."},{"role":"Secretary to Two Vice Presidents","organization":"W.R. Grace and Company (NY office)","start_year":1937,"end_year":1940,"notes":"Transferred to the New York office in 1937. Traveled repeatedly to South America."},{"role":"W.R. Grace Posting","organization":"W.R. Grace and Company (Medellín, Colombia)","start_year":1940,"notes":"Posted to Medellín, Colombia in 1940."}],"military_service":[{"war":"World War II","rank":"Battery Commander → Intelligence Officer (Army Air Corps)","unit":"New York's Seventh Regiment National Guard → Anti-Aircraft School (instructor) → Air Corps","allegiance":"United States","service_years":"1941-end of WWII","notes":"Enlisted in New York's Seventh Regiment, National Guard. Regiment entered federal service in 1941. After Pearl Harbor, commissioned at the Anti-Aircraft School and kept on as an instructor. Served as battery commander and intelligence officer, then transferred to classified work and finally to the Air Corps.","war_id":"WAR008"}],"bio":{"first_name":"Hugh","middle_name":"Gaylord","last_name":"Barclay","married_names":[],"suffix":"Jr.","display_name":"Hugh Gaylord Barclay Jr."},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"q